[src:druid-rust/data-binding] In computer programming, **data-binding** is a general technique that binds data sources from the provider and consumer together and synchronizes them.
[src:druid-rust/data-binding] This is usually done with two data/information sources with different languages, as in XML data binding and UI data binding.
[src:druid-rust/data-binding] In UI data binding, data and information objects of the same language, but different logic function are bound together (e.g., Java UI elements to Java objects).
[src:druid-rust/data-binding] In a data binding process, each data change is reflected automatically by the elements that are bound to the data.
[src:druid-rust/data-binding] The term data binding is also used in cases where an outer representation of data in an element changes, and the underlying data is automatically updated to reflect this change.
[src:druid-rust/data-binding] As an example, a change in a `TextBox` element could modify the underlying data value.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] In a graphical user interface (GUI), a **graphical widget** (also **graphical control element** or **control**) is an element of interaction, such as a button or a scroll bar.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] Controls are software components that a computer user interacts with through direct manipulation to read or edit information about an application.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] User interface libraries such as Windows Presentation Foundation, Qt, GTK, and Cocoa, contain a collection of controls and the logic to render these.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] Each widget facilitates a specific type of user-computer interaction, and appears as a visible part of the application's GUI as defined by the theme and rendered by the rendering engine.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] The theme makes all widgets adhere to a unified aesthetic design and creates a sense of overall cohesion.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] Some widgets support interaction with the user, for example labels, buttons, and check boxes.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] Others act as containers that group the widgets added to them, for example windows, panels, and tabs.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] Structuring a user interface with widget toolkits allows developers to reuse code for similar tasks, and provides users with a common language for interaction, maintaining consistency throughout the whole information system.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] Graphical user interface builders facilitate the authoring of GUIs in a WYSIWYG manner employing a user interface markup language.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] They automatically generate all the source code for a widget from general descriptions provided by the developer, usually through direct manipulation.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] Around 1920, *widget* entered American English, as a generic term for any useful device, particularly a product manufactured for sale; a gadget.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] In 1988, the term *widget* is attested in the context of Project Athena and the X Window System.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] The same year, in the manual *X Toolkit Widgets - C Language X Interface* by Ralph R.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] Finally, still in the same year, Ralph R.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] Any widget displays an information arrangement changeable by the user, such as a window or a text box.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] The defining characteristic of a widget is to provide a single interaction point for the direct manipulation of a given kind of data.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] In other words, widgets are basic visual building blocks which, combined in an application, hold all the data processed by the application and the available interactions on this data.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] GUI widgets are graphical elements used to build the human-machine-interface of a program.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] GUI widgets are implemented like software components.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] Widget toolkits and software frameworks, like e.g.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] GTK+ or Qt, contain them in software libraries so that programmers can use them to build GUIs for their programs.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] A family of common reusable widgets has evolved for holding general information based on the Palo Alto Research Center Inc. research for the Xerox Alto User Interface.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] Various implementations of these generic widgets are often packaged together in widget toolkits, which programmers use to build graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] Most operating systems include a set of ready-to-tailor widgets that a programmer can incorporate in an application, specifying how it is to behave.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] Each type of widget generally is defined as a class by object-oriented programming (OOP).
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] Therefore, many widgets are derived from class inheritance.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] In the context of an application, a widget may be *enabled* or *disabled* at a given point in time.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] An enabled widget has the capacity to respond to events, such as keystrokes or mouse actions.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] A widget that cannot respond to such events is considered disabled.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] The appearance of a widget typically differs depending on whether it is enabled or disabled; when disabled, a widget may be drawn in a lighter color ("**grayed out**") or be obscured visually in some way.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] On pop-up dialogues, buttons might appear greyed out shortly after appearance to prevent accidental clicking or inadvertent double-tapping.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] Widgets are sometimes qualified as *virtual* to distinguish them from their physical counterparts, e.g.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] *virtual* buttons that can be clicked with a pointer, vs. physical buttons that can be pressed with a finger (such as those on a computer mouse).
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] A related (but different) concept is the desktop widget, a small specialized GUI application that provides some visual information and/or easy access to frequently used functions such as clocks, calendars, news aggregators, calculators and desktop notes.
[src:druid-rust/graphical-widget] These kinds of widgets are hosted by a widget engine.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] In computing, **reactive programming** is a declarative programming paradigm concerned with data streams and the propagation of change.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] With this paradigm, it is possible to express static (e.g., arrays) or dynamic (e.g., event emitters) data streams with ease, and also communicate that an inferred dependency within the associated execution model exists, which facilitates the automatic propagation of the changed data flow.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] For example, in *imperative* programming, `a := b + c` would mean that `a` is being assigned the result of `b + c` at the time the expression is evaluated, and later, the values of `b` and `c` can be changed with no effect on the value of `a`.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] In contrast, in *reactive* programming, the value of `a` is automatically updated whenever the values of `b` or `c` change, without the program having to explicitly re-state the statement `a := b + c` to re-assign the value of `a`.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Another example is a hardware description language such as Verilog, where reactive programming enables changes to be modeled as they propagate through circuits.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has been proposed as a way to simplify creating interactive user interfaces and near-real-time computing animation.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] For example, in a model–view–controller (MVC) architecture, reactive programming can facilitate changes in an underlying *model* being reflected automatically in an associated *view*.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Several popular approaches are employed in creating reactive programming languages.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] One approach is the specification of *dedicated* languages that are specific to various *domain constraints*.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Such constraints usually are characterized by real-time, embedded computing or hardware description.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Another approach involves the specification of *general-purpose* languages that include support for reactivity.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Other approaches are articulated in the definition, and use of programming *libraries*, or *embedded domain-specific languages*, that enable reactivity alongside or atop a programming language.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Specification and use of these different approaches results in language *capability trade-offs*.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] In general, the more restricted a language is, the more its associated compilers and analysis programming tools are able to inform developers (e.g., in performing analysis for whether programs are able to execute in actual real-time).
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Functional trade-offs in specificity may result in deterioration of the general applicability of a language.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] A variety of models and semantics govern reactive programming.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Reactive programming language runtimes are represented by a graph that identifies the dependencies among the involved reactive values.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] In such a graph, *nodes* represent the act of computing, and *edges* model dependency relationships.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Such a runtime employs said graph, to help it keep track of the various computations, which must be executed anew, once an involved input changes value.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] At the implementation level, *event reaction* consists of the propagation across a graph's information, which characterizes the existence of change.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Consequently, computations that are affected by such change then become outdated and must be flagged for re-execution.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Such computations are then usually characterized by the transitive closure of the change (i.e., the full set of transitive dependencies a source affects) in its associated source.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] *Change propagation* may then lead to an update in the value of the graph's *sinks*.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Graph propagated information can consist of a node's complete state, i.e., the computation result of the involved node.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] In such cases, the node's previous output is then ignored.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Another method involves *delta propagation* i.e.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] In this case, information is proliferated along a graph's *edges,* which consist only of *delta*s describing how the previous node was changed.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] This approach is especially important when *nodes* hold large amounts of *state data*, which would otherwise be expensive to recompute from scratch.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Another common optimization is employment of *unary change accumulation* and *batch propagation*.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Such a solution can be faster because it reduces communication among involved nodes.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Optimization strategies can then be employed that reason about the nature of the changes contained within, and make alterations accordingly (e.g. two changes in the batch can cancel each other, and thus, simply be ignored).
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Yet another available approach, is described as *invalidity notification propagation*.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] This approach causes nodes with invalid input to pull updates, thus resulting in the update of their own outputs.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] A graph of dependencies is program-specific and generated by a programmer.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] When propagating changes, it is possible to pick propagation orders such that the value of an expression is not a natural consequence of the source program.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] We can illustrate this easily with an example.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Suppose `seconds` is a reactive value that changes every second to represent the current time (in seconds).
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Because `t` should always be greater than `seconds`, this expression should always evaluate to a true value.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Unfortunately, this can depend on the order of evaluation.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] When `seconds` changes, two expressions have to update: `seconds + 1` and the conditional.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] If the first evaluates before the second, then this invariant will hold.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] If, however, the conditional updates first, using the old value of `t` and the new value of `seconds`, then the expression will evaluate to a false value.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Some reactive languages are glitch-free and prove this property.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] This is usually achieved by topologically sorting expressions and updating values in topological order.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] This can, however, have performance implications, such as delaying the delivery of values (due to the order of propagation).
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Topological sorting of dependencies depends on the dependency graph being a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] In practice, a program may define a dependency graph that has cycles.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Usually, reactive programming languages expect such cycles to be "broken" by placing some element along a "back edge" to permit reactive updating to terminate.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Typically, languages provide an operator like `delay` that is used by the update mechanism for this purpose, since a `delay` implies that what follows must be evaluated in the "next time step" (allowing the current evaluation to terminate).
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Reactive languages typically assume that their expressions are purely functional.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] This allows an update mechanism to choose different orders in which to perform updates, and leave the specific order unspecified (thereby enabling optimizations).
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] When a reactive language is embedded in a programming language with state, however, it may be possible for programmers to perform mutable operations.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] How to make this interaction smooth remains an open problem.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] In some cases, it is possible to have principled partial solutions.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] In some reactive languages, the graph of dependencies is *static*, i.e., the graph is fixed throughout a program's execution.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] In other languages, the graph can be *dynamic*, i.e., it can change as the program executes.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Every second, the value of this expression changes to a different reactive expression, which `t + 1` then depends on.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Therefore, the graph of dependencies updates every second.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Permitting dynamic updating of dependencies provides significant expressive power (for instance, dynamic dependencies routinely occur in graphical user interface (GUI) programs).
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] However, the reactive update engine must decide whether to reconstruct expressions each time, or to keep an expression's node constructed but inactive; in the latter case, ensure that they do not participate in the computation when they are not supposed to be active.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Reactive programming languages can range from very explicit ones where data flows are set up by using arrows, to implicit where the data flows are derived from language constructs that look similar to those of imperative or functional programming.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] For example, in an implicitly lifted functional reactive programming (FRP), a function call might implicitly cause a node in a data flow graph to be constructed.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Reactive programming libraries for dynamic languages (such as the Lisp "Cells" and Python "Trellis" libraries) can construct a dependency graph from runtime analysis of the values read during a function's execution, allowing data flow specifications to be both implicit and dynamic.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Sometimes the term *reactive programming* refers to the architectural level of software engineering, where individual nodes in the data flow graph are ordinary programs that communicate with each other.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Reactive programming can be purely static where the data flows are set up statically, or be dynamic where the data flows can change during the execution of a program.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] The use of data switches in the data flow graph could to some extent make a static data flow graph appear as dynamic, and blur the distinction slightly.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] True dynamic reactive programming however could use imperative programming to reconstruct the data flow graph.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Reactive programming could be said to be of **higher order** if it supports the idea that data flows could be used to construct other data flows.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] That is, the resulting value out of a data flow is another data flow graph that is executed using the same evaluation model as the first.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Ideally all data changes are propagated instantly, but this cannot be assured in practice.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Instead, it might be necessary to give different parts of the data flow graph different evaluation priorities.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] This can be called **differentiated reactive programming**.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] For example, in a word processor, marking spelling errors need not be synchronized fully with adding or inserting characters.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Here, differentiated reactive programming can be used to give a spell checker lower priority, allowing it to be delayed while keeping other data flows more immediate.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] However, such differentiation introduces added design complexity.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] For example, deciding how to define the different data flow areas, and how to handle event passing between different data flow areas.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Evaluation of reactive programs is not necessarily based on how stack-based programming languages are evaluated.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Instead, when some data is changed, the change is propagated to all data that is derived partially or completely from the data that was changed.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] This change propagation could be achieved in a number of ways, where perhaps the most natural way is an invalidate/lazy-revalidate scheme.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] It could be problematic simply to naively propagate a change using a stack, because of potential exponential update complexity if the data structure has a certain shape.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] One such shape can be described as "repeated diamonds shape", and has the following structure: An→Bn→An+1, An→Cn→An+1, where n=1,2...
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] This problem could be overcome by propagating invalidation only when some data is not already invalidated, and later re-validate the data when needed using lazy evaluation.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] One inherent problem for reactive programming is that most computations that would be evaluated and forgotten in a normal programming language, needs to be represented in the memory as data-structures.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] This could potentially make reactive programming highly memory consuming.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] However, research on what is called *lowering* could potentially overcome this problem.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] On the other side, reactive programming is a form of what could be described as "explicit parallelism", and could therefore be beneficial for using the power of parallel hardware.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has principal similarities with the observer pattern commonly used in object-oriented programming.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] However, integrating the data flow concepts into the programming language would make it easier to express them and could therefore increase the granularity of the data flow graph.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] For example, the observer pattern commonly describes data flows between whole objects/classes, whereas object-oriented reactive programming could target the members of objects/classes.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] It is possible to fuse reactive programming with ordinary imperative programming.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] In such a paradigm, imperative programs operate upon reactive data structures.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Such a set-up is analogous to imperative constraint programming; however, while imperative constraint programming manages bidirectional data-flow constraints, imperative reactive programming manages one-way data-flow constraints.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] One reference implementation is the proposed Quantum runtime extension to JavaScript.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Object-oriented reactive programming (OORP) is a combination of object-oriented programming and reactive programming.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Perhaps the most natural way to make such a combination is this: instead of methods and fields, objects have *reactions* that automatically re-evaluate when the other reactions they depend on have been modified.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] If an OORP language maintains its imperative methods, it would also fall under the category of imperative reactive programming.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Functional reactive programming (FRP) is a programming paradigm for reactive programming on functional programming.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] The actor model (actors) is proposed to design reactive systems, often combined with functional reactive programming (FRP) and Reactive Streams to develop distributed reactive systems.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] A newer category of programming languages uses constraints (rules) as main programming concept.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] It consists of reactions to events, which keep all constraints satisfied.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] Not only does this facilitate event-based reactions, but it makes reactive programs instrumental to the correctness of software.
[src:druid-rust/reactive-programming] An example of a rule based reactive programming language is Ampersand, which is founded in relation algebra.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:druid-rust/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] Modularity is a specific application of concerns to system components (separation by size).
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] In modular systems, each module encapsulates a single concern, and modules are designed, implemented, and understood in isolation before being composed into a larger system.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] While modularity is the most common and recognizable embodiment of SoC in code structure, the principle of Separation of concerns is broader.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] For example, separating requirements analysis from implementation in a project timeline, or separating functional from non-functional requirements in a specification, are valid forms of separation of concerns that do not necessarily require a modular design.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] Dijkstra in his 1974 paper *"On the Role of Scientific Thought"*, coined the term *separation of concerns* in relation to software qualities such as *correctness* and *efficiency*.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] Carlo Ghezzi in his book "Fundamentals of software engineering" promotes Separation Of Concerns as the primary way to tackle the inherited complexity in software production.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] Philippe Kruchten in his article "Architectural Blueprints—The “4+1” View Model of Software Architecture" used a model composed of five main views to address large architectures, essentially this is a view-based separation of concerns, where each view focus on a different aspect of the architecture.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] Laplante, Phillip also mentioned that separation of concerns can be applied in software design, coding, time, and software qualities.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] The term *separation of concerns* was probably coined by Edsger W.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] Dijkstra in his 1974 paper "On the role of scientific thought".
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] Fifteen years later, it was evident the term *separation of concerns* was becoming an accepted idea.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] SoC is crucial to the design of the Internet.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] In the Internet protocol suite, great efforts have been made to separate concerns into well-defined layers.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] This allows protocol designers to focus on the concerns in one layer, and ignore the other layers.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] The Application Layer protocol SMTP, for example, is concerned about all the details of conducting an email session over a reliable transport service (usually TCP), but not in the least concerned about how the transport service makes that service reliable.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] Similarly, TCP is not concerned about the routing of data packets, which is handled at the Internet layer.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] HTML, CSS, and JavaScript are complementary languages used in the development of web pages and websites.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] HTML is mainly used for organization of webpage content, CSS is used for definition of content presentation style, and JavaScript defines how the content interacts and behaves with the user.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] Historically, this was not the case: prior to the introduction of CSS, HTML performed both duties of defining semantics and style.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] Subject-oriented programming allows separate concerns to be addressed as separate software constructs, each on an equal footing with the others.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] Each concern provides its own class-structure into which the objects in common are organized, and contributes state and methods to the composite result where they cut across one another.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] Correspondence rules describe how the classes and methods in the various concerns are related to each other at points where they interact, allowing composite behavior for a method to be derived from several concerns.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] Multi-dimensional SoC allows the analysis and composition of concerns to be manipulated as a multi-dimensional "matrix" in which each concern provides a dimension in which different points of choice are enumerated, with the cells of the matrix occupied by the appropriate software artifacts.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] Aspect-oriented programming allows cross-cutting concerns to be addressed as primary concerns.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] For example, most programs require some form of security and logging.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] Security and logging are often secondary concerns, whereas the primary concern is often on accomplishing business goals.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] However, when designing a program, its security must be built into the design from the beginning instead of being treated as a secondary concern.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] Applying security afterwards often results in an insufficient security model that leaves too many gaps for future attacks.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] This may be solved with aspect-oriented programming.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] For example, an aspect may be written to enforce that calls to a certain API are always logged, or that errors are always logged when an exception is thrown, regardless of whether the program's procedural code handles the exception or propagates it.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] In cognitive science and artificial intelligence, it is common to refer to David Marr's levels of analysis.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] At any given time, a researcher may be focusing on what some aspect of intelligence needs to compute, what algorithm it employs, or how that algorithm is implemented in hardware.
[src:druid-rust/separation-of-concerns] This separation of concerns is similar to the interface/implementation distinction in software and hardware engineering.
[src:druid-rust/widget-toolkit] A **widget toolkit**, **widget library**, **GUI toolkit**, **GUI framework**, **UI framework**, or **UX library** is a library or a collection of libraries containing a set of graphical control elements (called *widgets*) used to construct the graphical user interface (GUI) of programs.
[src:druid-rust/widget-toolkit] Most widget toolkits additionally include their own rendering engine.
[src:druid-rust/widget-toolkit] This engine can be specific to a certain operating system or windowing system or contain back-ends to interface with multiple ones and also with rendering APIs such as OpenGL, OpenVG, or EGL.
[src:druid-rust/widget-toolkit] The look and feel of the graphical control elements can be hard-coded or decoupled, allowing the graphical control elements to be themed/skinned.
[src:druid-rust/widget-toolkit] Some toolkits may be used from other languages by employing language bindings.
[src:druid-rust/widget-toolkit] Graphical user interface builders such as e.g.
[src:druid-rust/widget-toolkit] Glade Interface Designer facilitate the authoring of GUIs in a WYSIWYG manner employing a user interface markup language such as in this case GtkBuilder.
[src:druid-rust/widget-toolkit] The GUI of a program is commonly constructed in a cascading manner, with graphical control elements being added directly to on top of one another.
[src:druid-rust/widget-toolkit] Most widget toolkits use event-driven programming as a model for interaction.
[src:druid-rust/widget-toolkit] The toolkit handles user events, for example when the user clicks on a button.
[src:druid-rust/widget-toolkit] When an event is detected, it is passed on to the application where it is dealt with.
[src:druid-rust/widget-toolkit] The design of those toolkits has been criticized for promoting an oversimplified model of event-action, leading programmers to create error-prone, difficult to extend and excessively complex application code.
[src:druid-rust/widget-toolkit] Finite-state machines and hierarchical state machines have been proposed as high-level models to represent the interactive state changes for reactive programs.
[src:druid-rust/widget-toolkit] A window is considered to be a graphical control element.
[src:druid-rust/widget-toolkit] In some windowing systems, windows are added directly to the scene graph (canvas) by the window manager, and can be stacked and layered on top of each other through various means.
[src:druid-rust/widget-toolkit] Each window is associated with a particular application which controls the widgets added to its canvas, which can be watched and modified by their associated applications.
